  "prompt": "Can you sue a company for developing bad software?",
  "response": "Whether you can sue a company for bad software depends on several factors:\n\n1. Specific circumstances:\n- Was there demonstrable financial harm?\n- Did the software fail to perform as advertised?\n- Were there significant bugs or security vulnerabilities?\n\n2. Potential legal grounds:\n- Breach of contract\n- Breach of warranty\n- Negligence\n- Product liability\n\n3. Key considerations:\n- Most software licenses include liability disclaimers\n- Proving damages can be challenging\n- Legal costs might exceed potential recovery\n\n4. Common scenarios where legal action might be possible:\n- Software completely fails to work\n- Software causes direct financial losses\n- Serious security flaws lead to data breaches\n- Misrepresentation of software capabilities\n\n5. Recommended steps before litigation:\n- Document all issues\n- Communicate with the company\n- Seek refund or replacement\n- Consult with a technology or contract lawyer\n\nSuccess depends on specific details, evidence of harm, and ability to prove the company's liability. Not all bad software automatically qualifies for a lawsuit.\n\nConsulting a legal professional who specializes in technology or contract law would provide the most accurate guidance for your specific situation.",
